author: @husnainmaqsood9716
text: Instead of using signals for the creation of a new profile for every new user, we make some changes in the register function as follows:   def register(request):     if request.method == 'POST':         form = UserRegisterForm(request.POST)         if form.is_valid():             form.save()             new_user = User.objects.all().last()             new_user_profile = Profile.objects.create(user=new_user)             username = form.cleaned_data.get('username')             messages.success(request, 'Your account has been created successfully, Now you can Log In')             return redirect('login')     else:         form = UserRegisterForm()      context = {         'form': form,     }     return render(request, 'users/register.html', context)  This does the same work that messages were doing Whenever we are registering a user, at that time we create an object of profile for that user in the register function.

text: Ok so to whoever is having this error: ==== raise self.RelatedObjectDoesNotExist( django.contrib.auth.models.User.profile.RelatedObjectDoesNotExist: User has no profile.  ==== It drove me crazy! The signals were not working at all. Meaning, the Profile was neither created nor saved. I tried all the "fixes" people mentioned, nothing worked!  My issue was that, when we added the User App to the settings.py (check part 6 of the tutorial), I added it this way: under the list of INSTALLED_APPS, I created another list (for separation) and called it MY_APPS and added the Users App as follows: INSTALLED_APPS = [ .... ..... ]  MY_APPS = [     ....     'users',    ]  INSTALLED_APPS.extend(MY_APPS)  Now, that did the trick. Everything worked. Profile created and saved and all good. Out of a sudden, it just didn't work and started getting the above-mentioned error. Doing: MY_APPS = [     ....     'users.apps.UsersConfig'    ] or simply add it to INSTALLED_APPS  Dammit!

author: @codenaman
text: Great Teacher... respect from bottom my heart... :).     But if someone get the RelatedObjectsDoesNotExists Exception after adding the signals..  please try with below code. in signals.py  from django.db.models.signals import post_save  from django.contrib.auth.models import User  from django.dispatch import receiver  from .models import Profile from django.core.exceptions import ObjectDoesNotExist  @receiver(post_save, sender=User) def create_profile(sender, instance, created, **kwargs):     if created:         Profile.objects.create(user=instance) # creating the profile object   @receiver(post_save, sender=User) def create_profile(sender, instance, **kwargs):     try:         instance.profile.save()     except ObjectDoesNotExist:         Profile.objects.create(user=instance)   I hope it will help.. :)

author: @steves1015
text: Thank you for the great content! Ive been following the series and on this latest one I experienced an issue with the profiles. Which others may run into. I deleted all the profiles created, even for the current superuser.  I logged out and tried to log back in again, but it threw a tantrum and would not let me. It kept giving me an error of user profile not found.  I guess it would need some form of error handling, but the only way i could get around this was to go into the database and manually add a profile for the superuser. Then I could get access back to the admin page :(  Also, anyone trying to add extra fields to the tables, unfortunately there is an issue that once a table has been created; if you attempt to update and put in more tables, then you have got to give default values for each field or specify the fields as not required. This even happens if the database is completely empty. Its a bit of a pain, but i would think it was there to protect database integrity. You can specify a default value and then get users to change the values, or you could specify blank=True to allow it update the table, and then change this back later to make it a required field..

author: @autogc22
text: Thanks Mr.Schafer. These are the best Django tutorials. For those like me that don't follow your steps one by one, I faced the problem of try to login with my admin user with all the code already written, without first creating manually a profile for this user, so Django rise an exception ObjectDoesNotExist as, of course, user doesn't has a profile. I haven't been able to catch this exception (Django says it' not defined) but, following this recommendations https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26270042/how-do-you-catch-this-exception/26270785#26270785, I've been able to solve the problem like this:  def save_or_create_profile_for_existing_user(sender, instance, **kwargs):        try:         # if the user has a profile, save it         instance.profile.save()     except Profile.DoesNotExist:         # if the user doesn't has a profile, create it        Profile.objects.create(user=instance)  just in case somebody face the same issue. Thanks again Mr.Schafer PS. More info about these exceptions here https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.7/ref/exceptions/#django.core.exceptions.ObjectDoesNotExist

author: @vighnesh153
text: If the profile doesn't get created automatically, in the project's settings.py file, in the INSTALLED_APPS list, instead of adding APPNAME to the list, add APPNAME.apps.AppnameConfig to the list. Else, the default configuration will be django.apps.AppConfig which is what we inherited in apps.py  and added a ready method to it.

author: @gk2011
text: So I had some issues with this one in regards to the default picture not showing up. If you are having this issue.  1. Make sure its in the media directory not the profile_pics directory 2. You can use the inspect element interface on your website(Right click the blank image and hit "inspect element" this will highlight the picture and tell you where its looking for the link to the image) 3. If when doing this it does not display anything, then it means the account does not have a profile, go into admin and make one. I spent an hour and a half searching code to finally figure this dumb error on my part out. 4. Make sure whatever image you use is a jpeg if you are following the code perfectly 5. Figuring these problems out if half the fun. Don't get frustrated!

author: @NobleStories1
text: Hi for those who have a problemes in debuggin run this instruction before (python manage.py runserver)   Install Dependencies  1 (pip install -r requirements.txt)  Set Database (Make Sure you are in directory same as manage.py)   2 (pip install pillow)  3 (python manage.py makemigrations) 4 (python manage.py migrate)  Create SuperUser  5 (python manage.py createsuperuser)   After all these steps , you can start testing and developing this project.  6( python manage.py runserver)   That's it! Happy Coding!
